Inflation in Europe has hit the food market.
Accelerated inflation, measured in the euro area, is mainly due to the rapid increase in food prices.
In November, the increase in prices in the 13 euro area countries was more significant compared to forecasts, after an inflation rate of 2.6 per cent in October, an annual inflation of 3.1 per cent was recorded, the European Community Statistics Office in Luxembourg said.
Official forecasts have indicated only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
Unlike U.S., British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the key interest rate by saying that the decline in interest rates, with commodity prices rising and unemployment falling, would lead to the generation of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep the inflation rate below but close to two per cent.
According to one analyst, it is Catch 22 for the ECB: “we must deter” inflation in order not to have to intervene on this subject any longer.
In Germany, the inflation rate of 3.3 percent is a record over the past twelve years and in Spain, it has risen from 3.6 to 4.1.
Inflation in the euro area has taken off due to the rapid rise in food and energy prices.
The futures market for cereals has increased by 88 per cent and the price of soybeans has also reached its highest value since 1973.
The price of food oil and dairy products also increased significantly in 2007.
This year, the global oil price rose 52 percent, and last month, a barrel of black gold cost nearly $100.
According to the ECB, in 2008, the inflation rate will increase from 2.1, this year to 2.5 per cent, but in 2009 it will fall to 1.9.
According to analysts, the 12-month inflation rate remains around 3 percent, however, in the next 3 to 4 months, the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to reduce the guiding rate twice in 2008.
