Many hospitals are making savings on disinfectants.
This year, more than a thousand infections, caused mainly by the incorrect use of antibiotics, have been recorded in hospitals.
The hygienic conditions of hospitals, the insufficient number of beds, the overcrowding of medical personnel do not help to block infections, says the chief physician of the National Epidemiology Centre.
Many hospitals also make savings on disinfectants.
Not long ago an MRSA infection was diagnosed at the traumatology department of the J<0xC3><0xA1>nos hospital.
Antibiotic-resistant bacteria have been detected in a hospitalized man following a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year a similar infection occurred in the same place.
The victim of a serious car accident left the hospital but soon after he had to return due to an MRSA infection and, since then, doctors have not been able to do him an important operation because of the bacteria that is in his body.
Until 10 December this year, 1,094 hospital infections generated by a multidrug-resistant pathogen were reported to the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, said Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz, chief physician at the National Epidemiology Center.
Namely, it is the number of infections caused by a multidrug-resistant pathogen that has actually been recorded in hospitals and for the rest we have no information.
About two-thirds of infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, i.e. by methicillin-oxacillin-resistant staphylococcus aureus.
One-third of people carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without developing a disease.
Infections caused by SAs (such as angina, amygdalitis, skin infections, traumatic infections) respond well to antibiotics, they are easily curable.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or inappropriately, the bacterium, which responds well to antibiotics, will develop a bacterium that is well resistant to antibiotics that will proliferate quickly in bad hospital conditions.
In case of temporary or prolonged malfunction of the immune system, this bacterium can cause serious hospital infections, such as a traumatic infection or septicemia, on elderly patients, small weights or having a weakened organism.
According to the director of the J<0xC3><0xA1>nos hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infections, these infections are part of the daily life of hospitals.
Above all, we should not confuse the infection with the epidemic, we do not find MRSA only, or we do not look for them, said Tibor Nyulasi.
SAs are resistant to antibiotics.
“These patients are isolated, the nursing staff put on rubber gloves and protective masks and we have antibiotics adapted to treat them,” said Tibor Nyulasi.
A priori, hospitalized patients are examined if they are carriers of MRSA, however, the infection cannot always be avoided.
The sampling of the sample is not in fashion
The vast majority of infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but current conditions and circumstances are not favorable in Hungarian hospitals to prevent the development and proliferation of multidrug-resistant pathogens, says Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz.
As this infection manifests itself mainly in hospitals and seniors’ residences, hospitals should control hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients with MRSA.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
It should be noted that the National Social Security Fund does not fund these reviews.
Most cases can only be seen if MRSA infection is detectable on the patient, said the head doctor of the epidemiology center.
The European Union has rigorous recommendations on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also Hungarian guidelines for the cure of certain infections and syndromes.
Efforts must be made to target antibiotic therapy, i.e. microbiological tests should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always take this into account.
Microbiological sampling is even rarer in outpatient and basic care, Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz said.
Many hospitals are making savings on disinfectants.
Scientific evidence shows that MRSAs proliferated from one patient to another most often through medical personnel.
It is therefore essential to wash your hands, put on gloves and protective masks, but important gaps are detected in hospitals also in this area.
MRSA proliferated by infection transmitted by inhalation of droplets and by contact. However, due to the conditions in Hungarian hospitals, the infected patient cannot always be isolated.
In addition, the rooms are often full, the beds are often too close to each other while in terms of epidemic, the patients should be kept away from each other by a minimum of 1.5 meters.
Unfortunately, we also find that hospitals, in difficult financial situations, make savings on disinfectants, they lack nurses, the patients are numerous, so the risk of contamination is even greater, Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz said.
According to Karolina B<0xC3><0xB6>r<0xC3><0xB6>cz, in hospitals or preventive measures are respected, the number of infections is demonstrably lower or then the proliferation of the pathogen can be blocked.
Government project against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA infection represents exorbitant expenses for social security funds, which is why we fight this infection everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has established a program to prevent or reduce the incidence of MRSA.
According to the published data, this program is effective and MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) sets out among its priorities the prevention of the incidence of multidrug-resistant pathogens (such as MRSAs) as well as the prevention of hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
