In Hungary, the law defines exactly the holidays and, around the holidays, it has become common practice to reorganize the working days, the number of which will decrease next year.
The holidays are not uniform in the EU and the US either.
Hungarian legislation distinguishes national and state holidays as well as rest days.
Rest days are often associated with religious holidays or important historical events.
In Hungary, we celebrate the new year, the last day of the year that ends and the first day of the new year are also days of rest, the latter especially so that the wakers can rest peacefully.
In a year, we have eleven red-marked parties.
March 15 is a national holiday, commemorating the revolution of 1848, as well as October 23 which is the commemorative day of the revolution of 1956.
On August 20, we celebrate the constitution of our state, on May 1 is the feast of labor and on November 1 and 2, we remember members of our family and our deceased friends.
In addition, we have two days at Easter, at Pentecost and at Christmas.
The days of our state holidays, national or even religious that rarely fall on a weekend, according to the calendar, it has become common to reorganize the working days in cases or there is only one working day left before or after the holiday marked in red.
It is true that we pay the price of the extended weekends by working or going to school on the Saturday preceding the extended weekend.
For many years, the Minister of Labour has ruled in a special regulation on the days of replacement of the days before or after the holidays.
The law extends to all employers and to all their employees, civil servants and persons working in the public service.
However, it does not apply to service companies, institutions that run uninterruptedly and in service, by their vocation, and also to days of rest.
This year, the working days will be changed only around the end of the year holidays: from December 24, life stops almost all over the country because according to experiments most people do overtime or take holidays that they have saved for these purposes to be able to spend the days between Christmas and New Year's Day.
Next year many holidays fall in the middle or at the end of the week, so there will be fewer changes in working days compared to this year.
The schedule will be reorganised for the first time around the Labor Day to allow employees to stay at home for four consecutive days.
Saturday 25 April will be a working day to have a rest day on Friday 2 May.
Another change is planned for October 23: Saturday, October 18, will be a working day replacing Friday, October 24.
On the other hand, next year, the end of the year is announced under the sign of the holidays because from December 24, everyone will take a non-stop break even if the day of the new year falls on a Wednesday.
