The U.S. Federal Reserve Bank, the European Central Bank and the British, Swiss and Canadian central banks have decided to fight the financial markets crisis together.
Over one hundred billion dollars will thus be placed on the monetary markets through auctions.
It will be for the banks to sell, through an auction system, the interest rates at which they are willing to borrow money.
As an example, the US Fed will send $40 billion to the auctions and, in addition, it will provide 24 billion to the European and Swiss central banks.
This is the first time since the attacks on 11 September that the central banks of individual states have decided to take action at this concerted point, aimed at preventing or even reducing the effects of the financial crisis.
“This approach tends to address the major problems of the economy, namely the growing lack of free capital that banks could lend,” Bernard Baumohl of the consulting firm Economic Outlook Group wrote in his report to clients.
“The concerted action of the central banks has reduced the likelihood of a recession in the United States from 65 percent to about 50 percent,” Baumohl said in his report.
Banks have already lost $60 billion due to unreimbursed loans, especially in the United States.
Analysts are still waiting for more losses in billions.
“If the central banks have chosen this approach, it’s that they really need to understand what can still go on,” said ABN chief economist Amro Kieran Davies.
“It looks like the situation is really bad,” he added.
The central banks fear that if the banks themselves have difficult access to loans, they will lend more to their clients.
This would reduce consumption and plunge the U.S. economy into a recession that could impact global economic growth.
The central banks made this choice after they failed to bring down the London interbank rate, called LIBOR, used to borrow on the interbank market.
This meant that banks were still afraid of mutual loans, even though the U.S., Canadian and English central banks had repeatedly reduced their interest rates during the fall.
“This will have the same effect as a new interest rate drop,” Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting told Reuters.
Some analysts do not believe that the central bank’s approach will not help to curb the crisis, as it does not address the main problem that is the fall of the real estate market in the US.
