“It is regrettable that the parties have not been able to reach an agreement on the status,” European mediator Wolfgang Ischinger said at a press conference in Vienna.
Noting that peace in the region was "at stake", his US counterpart, Frank Wisner, urged Belgrade and Pristina to respect their commitments to preserve peace and dialogue beyond the end of the negotiations.
“We do not foresee violence immediately, but we are entering a very difficult period,” he added, referring to “obvious tensions.”
End of Mediation on December 10
The troika mediators, which brings together the European Union, the United States and Russia, will visit Serbia and Kosovo for the last time on Monday.
The province’s 90%-populated future could become clearer when Ischinger, Wisner and Russian mediator Alexander Botsane-Khartchenko deliver their report to the UN Security Council by December 10.
The Baden talks, near Vienna, were the sixth and final session of negotiations since the troika was charged with a new mediation by the United Nations last August.
Americans and Europeans believe that their mediation will end on December 10.
The Russians, who have already blocked the Security Council from granting independence to Kosovo, are insisting on continuing negotiations beyond this deadline.
“Russia was and remains committed to a negotiated solution, a compromise solution,” Botsane-Khartchenko said.
Is it a unilateral declaration of independence?
After eight years of UN administration in Kosovo, the West believes that EU-supervised independence is the only viable solution.
Pristina says she is ready to declare it unilaterally if the Security Council does not decide in her favour.
Belgrade insists on increased autonomy.
"Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached," Kosovo Autonomous Authority President Fatmir Sejdiu said at the hotel in Baden, where these "last chance negotiations" took place since Monday.
Hashim Thaci, former commander of the Kosovar rebellion and future prime minister of the province, expressed his regrets.
But he added that the autonomy plan presented by Belgrade “belonged to a past that led to murder and deportation.”
"Domino effect"
Serbian President Boris Tadic said a compromise was still conceivable, warning the Albanian majority of Kosovo against the consequences of a unilateral proclamation of the province's independence.
Belgrade says in particular to fear a “domino effect” in a region still weakened by the 1990s independence wars.
“For Serbia,” he said, “it does not mean that a compromise is impossible.”
On Tuesday, the Serbian delegation had insisted that any decision be returned exclusively to the Security Council, where its Russian ally has a veto.
