A heavy memory
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which trace the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are in free access.
The 47 million records stored on 27 km of the line in Bad Arolsen (Hesse) were only available for "humanitarian" purposes, i.e. individually and nominally, at the request of an ex-victim or his right-holders.
The eleven states in charge of their management - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to researchers and historians.
The process of ratification of this agreement by all States has been completed, and the opening has been effective since yesterday.
Sensitive Information
Historians’ access to Bad Arolsen will allow research to be conducted “in particular on the displacement of prisoners, the population of camps and the health of forced workers,” says Reto Meistern, the director of these archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, including Germany, opposed the public opening of these nomination documents, due to the sensitive nature of certain information.
Such as the supposed homosexuality or mental disability of certain victims of deportation.
The records of the concentration camps or arrest warrants established by the Gestapo had been collected after the war for a practical purpose: to find the civilians deported or subjected to forced labour and, if necessary, to provide them with proof of their internment, in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Even today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees handle tens of thousands of individual applications.
However, for a part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
“There is nothing fundamentally new to expect from these documents,” said Prof. Wolfgang Benz, director of the Center for Research on Anti-Semitism at the Technische Universit<0xC3><0xA4>t in Berlin in 2006.
