Venus is the infernal twin of the Earth.
Despite its hostile atmosphere to life, Venus looks more like Earth than previously thought: the European space probe Venus Express has discovered flashes in the atmosphere and wind gusts at the poles, similar to those that appear in winter on Earth.
For almost three decades, scientists have assumed that there are lights on Venus.
The European "Venus Express" probe today brought evidence of this - it detected electromagnetic waves at the limit of the atmosphere: the lights on Venus burst at a height of about 56 kilometers of cloud clouds, reports Christopher Russel of the University of California at Los Angeles.
According to the famous theory of cypress, lightning would have made life appear on Earth: the storm would have stimulated reactions in the oceans that led to the formation of amino acids, the cornerstone of life.
This is not the case on Venus: “If there was life, it must have been at a very ancient date in history,” says Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today there should be little living things on the surface of Venus: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, there are sometimes temperatures of 500 degrees.
“Venus may be the infernal twin of the Earth, but it remains a twin,” Russell said.
Why Venus, which looks so much like Earth in mass and dimensions, has been hit with such a different evolution, is the fundamental question of the ASE mission.
The departure of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was an important step in Venetian research, as no more probes were on the way for exploration of this planet since the 1980s.
In the opinion of the researchers, the most recent research results that have now been presented in several articles of "Nature" not only emphasize the uniqueness of Venus within the solar system.
They also show that the common points with the Earth of our neighboring planet are more numerous than assumed at first.
So the researchers found, in addition to the wind gusts already known at the north pole, a cloud gust at the south pole, which rotates much faster.
The phenomenon recalls the air currents in the Earth's hemispheres in winter, writes a team of researchers around Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second planet in the solar system has almost the same mass as Earth and is, with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers, almost as large.
The planet, known as a star in the evening or in the morning, revolves around the sun in just 225 days.
However, it turns much more slowly on itself: a Venusian day lasts 243 Earth days.
Although Venus, with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, hardly resembles the Earth, scientists assume that the two planets were formed under similar conditions.
On both, water accumulated and remained on Earth in the form of oceans, but was lost in space on Venus.
And while carbon dioxide has settled on Earth in the form of carbonate, it makes up most of the atmosphere on Venus.
