They're not Warhol's safes.
The one who connects the concepts of Sweden and falls into wood, thinks of Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
Or if?
At the moment, wooden boxes made in Sweden cast shadows on Warhol’s list of works.
A large part of the eighty Brillo-Boxes of "Type Stockholm" listed there are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" questioned the authenticity of the Brillo-Boxs of 1968 by Andy Warhol a few months ago, the internal research of the Moderna Museet in Stockholm today resulted in a disenchanting result: the six "Brillo-Boxes" from the "Brillo-Boxes", of which the "Brillo-Boxes" from the "Brillo-Boxes", the "Brillo-Boxes" from the "Brill", and the "Brillo-Boxes" from the same" are from the same.
The ancient history is interwoven, a disconcerting chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created his first "Brillo-Boxes" in New York, painted wooden boxes, which are based on the red-blue-white design of "Brillo" powdered soapboards.
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet presented in 1968 - with Warhol's agreement - hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: These were not from Warhol (for financial reasons) but had been delivered directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
These were not works of art here, but rather their models, samples of exhibitions.
At the same time, Warhol had given permission in 1968 to produce some Brillo wooden boxes in Sweden, which were not exhibited at the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses of the time today speak of about fifteen wooden boxes that at the time would have entered law into the history of art and auctions, as Andy Warhol's original Brillo-Boxes allowed, with the name "Type Stockholm".
Some of them have reached more than $100,000 in auction sales.
The problem now is that the legendary director of the Pontus Hultén Museum wrongly claimed, later, that about one hundred wooden crates had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol would then have given to him.
In fact, the 105 Hultén boxes were produced in Malm<0xC3><0xB6> only in 1990, for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By that time, Warhol had already been dead for three years.
Lars Bystr<0xC3><0xB6>m, curator in charge of the Moderna Museet, examined, alongside the museum’s six Brillo-Boxes, three other Swedish private collections, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their laminated panels were first printed and polished with a brush, and then the appliqué.
On the contrary, the texture of the copies dating from 1990 reveals that the painting was applied directly without a layer of background on the laminated panels, using a paint roller - in addition, it is not an oil painting, but an acrylic.
"These boxes were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from Andy Warhol's official Brillo-Boxes list," Lars Nittve, director of the Moderna Museet, said: "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York doesn't collect any of these, Moderna will collect any other decisions.
Already in July, the Authentication Board of course announced that it would investigate the "heavy accusations" that will be raised in the case of powdered soap boxes.
But since then, there has been an inexorable silence.
